is the map $x \mapsto 2x \text{mod}(1)$. This map is known as the
'unilateral shift' because, in the binary number system this map
shifts all digits to the left by one decimal place, and truncates the
integer. The second most commonly used paradigm of chaos is the Smale
horseshoe whose complexity is essentially the bilateral shift obtained
when we simply shift without truncation in some symbol system. Neither
of these paradigms fully explains chaos since shifts cannot generate
